--|\n| **Repository lifecycle** | `open()` | 43–85 | Git repo discovery &amp; `.h5i/` initialization |\n| **Core Git commit** | `commit()` | 91–281 | Creates commits + orchestrates AST scanning, test tracking, metadata persistence to `.h5i/` |\n| **Log APIs** | `get_log()`, `h5i_log()`, `get_log_at_branch()`, `print_log()` | 287–651 | Retrieves commit history with AI/test/AST metadata |\n| **Causal chains** | `causal_ancestors()`, `causal_dependents()` | 656–727 | Traverses caused-by links in commit graphs |\n| **Blame/ancestry** | `blame()`, `blame_by_ast()`, `blame_ancestry()` | 732–1084 | Line-level provenance by git blame + AST hashing |\n| **Metadata** | `load_h5i_record()`, `read_pending_context()`, `record_human_prompt()`, `list_ai_commits()`, `build_intent_graph()` | 1089–2232 | AI provenance, context branching, intent graphs |\n| **Conflict resolution** | `merge_file_three_way()` | 1147–1225 | Three-way merge handling |\n| **Content access** | `get_blob_at_head()`, `get_content_at_oid()`, `diff_ast()`, `save_ast_to_sidecar()` | 1230–2160 | File retrieval + AST storage/diffing |\n| **Test/integrity** | `scan_test_metrics()`, `load_test_results_from_file()`, `verify_integrity()`, `verify_commit_integrity()`, `cochanged_files()` | 2160–2700+ | Test discovery + integrity rules + review scoring |\n\n**Cross-cutting internal helpers:** 30+ private functions (fn lines 26–3248) scattered across the file, including:\n- `blame_by_line()`, `map_line_to_parent()` (blame internals)\n- `load_ast_at_commit()`, `load_ast_blob()` (AST internals)\n- `scan_test_block()` (test extraction)\n- `get_staged_diff()`, `get_head_commit()` (git helpers)\n- Parser subprocess management (`run_parser_subprocess()`, `find_parser_script()`)\n\n**Coupling:** H5iRepository directly imports from 4 internal modules:\n- **blame** (line 9): `AncestryEntry`, `BlameMode`, `BlameResult`\n- **metadata** (lines 14–17): `AiMetadata`, `CommitSummary`, `H5iCommitRecord`, `IntegrityLevel`, `IntentEdge`, `IntentGraph`, `IntentNode`, `IntegrityReport`, `PendingContext`, `TestMetrics`, `TestSource`, `Decision`\n- **error** (line 11): `H5iError`\n\n**Verdict:** H5iRepository is a **high-cohesion, low-separation-of-concerns facade**. It wraps git2 and orchestrates everything—it's not just a repository handle, it's the system's orchestrator. Methods touch AST, metadata, tests, causal links, and blame all in one struct. While the commit-time workflows are grouped logically by section comments, the object itself spans data model, storage layer, analysis (blame/blame_ancestry), and policy enforcement (verify_integrity).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Module Dependency Graph\n\n**Findings:** \n\n**High-coupling clients of H5iRepository:**\n- **server.rs** (6 crate:: imports): imports `H5iRepository`, `ctx`, `memory`, `metadata`, `review`, `session_log`\n- **compliance.rs** (6 imports): imports `H5iRepository`, `policy`, `metadata`, `injection`, `error`, `session_log`\n- **resume.rs** (5 imports): imports `H5iRepository`, `ctx`, `memory`, `error`, `session_log`\n- **mcp.rs** (5 imports): imports `H5iRepository`, `ctx`, `blame`, `claims`, `session_log`\n- **pr.rs** (4 imports): imports `H5iRepository`, `ctx`, `metadata`, `error`\n\n**Layering:** The sandbox stack (env, sandbox, container, cgroup) shows **clean, well-separated dependencies**:\n\n```\nenv.rs\n  ├─→ crate::error\n  ├─→ crate::objects (captures log)\n  └─→ crate::sandbox (IsolationClaim, ResolvedPolicy, BoxGitPath)\n\nsandbox.rs\n  └─→ crate::error (pure policy definitions, no upward deps)\n\ncontainer.rs\n  ├─→ crate::error\n  ├─→ crate::objects (EgressHost, EgressSummary)\n  └─→ crate::sandbox (ExecOutcome, NetMode, Profile, ResolvedPolicy)\n\ncgroup.rs\n  └─ (no crate:: imports — pure kernel interface helpers)\n```\n\n**No circular imports detected.**\n\nStorage-related modules form a clean tier:\n- **storage.rs** → `error` (validation &amp; repair helpers)\n- **objects.rs** → `error`, `token_filter` (content-addressed capture store)\n- **env.rs** → `error`, `sandbox`, `objects` (env orchestration)\n\n**Verdict:** The **sandbox/confinement subsystem is well-layered**. `sandbox.rs` is a pure policy module with no upward dependencies. `cgroup.rs` has zero internal dependencies (Unix syscall wrapper). `container.rs` and `env.rs` depend downward on sandbox + objects, forming a clear stack. This is the **inverse of repository.rs**—high separation of concerns.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Error Handling: Mixed Strategies\n\n**Finding:** The codebase uses both **thiserror** and **anyhow**, creating two error regimes:\n\n**thiserror (H5iError):**\n- Defined in error.rs (62 lines): `#[derive(Error, Debug)]`\n- Used by: repository.rs, sandbox.rs, env.rs, container.rs, storage.rs, all core modules\n- Type-safe, structured errors with context attachment (lines 53–59): `IoWithContext { path, source }`\n- All internal Result&lt;T&gt; is Result&lt;T, H5iError&gt; (repository.rs lines 26–1895 are 100% H5iError)\n\n**anyhow (ad hoc):**\n- Only **2 files** use it: mcp.rs (line 48), pr.rs (line 1-2)\n- **Inconsistent in repository.rs itself:**\n  - `pub fn print_log()` returns `anyhow::Result&lt;()&gt;` (line 468)\n  - `pub fn print_intent_graph()` returns `anyhow::Result&lt;()&gt;` (line 1615)\n  - All other public methods return `Result&lt;T, H5iError&gt;`\n\n**Verdict:** Error handling is **mostly coherent but has leaky exceptions**:\n- Core library uses thiserror (correct, enables error recovery)\n- Two clients (mcp.rs, pr.rs) use anyhow (acceptable for tools/CLI)\n- Repository.rs has **2 anyhow outliers** in print methods (inconsistent w/ 40+ typed methods)\n  - These should either return H5iError or anyhow wrapping should be transparent\n\n**Recommendation:** Audit those 2 print methods—likely just convenience formatting, could use `map_err(|e| anyhow::anyhow!(\"{}\", e))` or return H5iError.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Sandbox Stack Responsibilities: Well Split\n\n**env.rs (~500 lines, including per-env state machine):**\n- Orchestrates isolated workspaces (git worktrees under `.git/.h5i/env/`)\n- Event log + manifest persistence to `refs/h5i/env/meta`\n- Runs a command inside the resolved isolation tier (process/container/etc.)\n- Lifecycle: created → running → idle → proposed → applied\n- Clear import: `uses crate::sandbox`, `crate::objects`, `crate::error`\n\n**sandbox.rs (~260 lines, policy + claims):**\n- Pure data types: `IsolationClaim` (Workspace/Process/Supervised/Container), `NetMode`, `Profile`, `ResolvedPolicy`\n- No orchestration; no reverse dependencies\n- Parser for `.h5i/env.toml` policies\n- Resource caps, probing logic (fail-closed on unsupported kernels)\n- Single downward import: `crate::error`\n\n**container.rs (~800 lines, Podman adapter):**\n- Rootless Podman shell-out for `isolation=container`\n- HTTP/HTTPS egress proxy (L7 allowlist when `net.egress` is set)\n- Hardening: `--cap-drop=ALL`, `--rm`, read-only rootfs, `--userns=keep-id`\n- Clear dependencies: `error`, `objects` (for egress tallying), `sandbox` (policy types)\n\n**cgroup.rs (~180 lines, v2 resource control):**\n- Rootless cgroup v2 helpers (`memory.max`, `pids.max`)\n- Probes for delegated subtree; fails closed if unavailable\n- Zero internal dependencies (direct syscall/procfs I/O)\n\n**Verdict:** **Excellent separation.** Each module has a single concern:\n- `sandbox.rs`: **Policy definition**\n- `cgroup.rs`: **Resource accounting** (Linux only)\n- `container.rs`: **Container runtime adapter**\n- `env.rs`: **Workspace/lifecycle orchestration**\n\nNo god objects, no circular coupling. Clear data flow downward (env calls sandbox + container).\n\n---\n\n### 6. Summary of Design Smells &amp; Strengths\n\n**SMELLS:**\n\n1. **H5iRepository as orchestrator** (~3.7K lines)\n   - Touches AST, metadata, tests, blame, integrity rules, causal chains\n   - No internal trait boundaries; all methods public on one struct\n   - Makes it hard to test/mock individual concerns\n   - Fixes: Extract `BlameEngine`