onfinement (Landlock/seccomp/cgroup), MCP server, web HTTP server, PR tooling, and context-workspace reasoning\n\n**Code size distribution** (src/*.rs):\n- main.rs: 10,261 lines (enum + CLI routing, no feature gates)\n- ctx.rs: 5,724 lines (context workspace, 107 tests = 1.9%)\n- server.rs: 5,172 lines (web UI backend, 10 tests = 0.2%)\n- env.rs: 4,249 lines (sandbox orchestration, 19 tests = 0.4%)\n- pr.rs: 3,984 lines (GitHub PR tooling, 71 tests = 1.8%)\n- repository.rs: 3,704 lines (Git + h5i refs, 31 tests = 0.8%)\n\n---\n\n### 2. SERVER.RS: WEB UI BACKEND (NOT A SIDECAR)\n\n**Finding: Comprehensive read-only analytics dashboard, core to h5i's reasoning system.**\n\n**Purpose**: `h5i serve --port 8080` is a **read-only HTTP analytics server** exposing git history, context state, and sandbox metrics. Not a separate sidecar—it's the user-facing dashboard for understanding what the CLI recorded.\n\n**Route inventory** (47 handler functions across 5,172 lines):\n- **Git/commit surface** (7 endpoints):\n  - `/api/repo`, `/api/branches`, `/api/commits`, `/api/commit-files`\n  - `/api/integrity`, `/api/integrity/commit`, `/api/intent-graph`\n- **Context workspace** (8 endpoints):\n  - `/api/context/{status,snapshots,show,milestones,diff,relevant,search,dag,promotion}`\n- **Memory/session** (6 endpoints):\n  - `/api/memory/{snapshots,diff}`, `/api/session-log/{,list,churn}`\n- **Sandbox environment** (3 endpoints):\n  - `/api/envs`, `/api/env/probe`, `/api/env/:agent/:slug{,/captures/:id}`\n- **Legacy UI** (embedded assets): `/`, `/v2/`, `/assets/*`\n\n**Test coverage**: Only 10 tests (0.2% of lines)—the integration test suite (`sandbox_api.rs`: 4 tests) boots the router and exercises a few key endpoints. **No unit tests** of individual handlers; coverage relies on CLI integration tests.\n\n**Observation**: This is *not* scope creep. The server is the **visualization layer** for h5i's git-backed reasoning. Removing it would cripple observability. However, the thin test layer (10 tests across 5K lines) suggests the surface is high-risk during refactors.\n\n---\n\n### 3. CTX.RS: CONTEXT WORKSPACE DATA MODEL\n\n**Finding: A multi-ref, DAG-based reasoning memory overlaid on Git.**\n\n**Architecture**: Context branches are stored as parallel Git refs under `refs/h5i/context/&lt;name&gt;`, not a single monolithic tree. This is a redesign from legacy (`refs/h5i/context` as a single ref with internal `branches/&lt;name&gt;/` subtrees).\n\n**Data model** (per context branch):\n```\nrefs/h5i/context/&lt;name&gt; tree:\n├── commit.md          # Milestone summaries (append-only)\n├── trace.md           # Human-readable OTA log (rendered)\n├── ephemeral.md       # Scratch traces cleared on context commit\n├── metadata.yaml      # File structure, deps, env config\n└── dag.json           # Trace-node DAG (derivable from git log, kept for fast reads)\n\nrefs/h5i/context/main (additionally):\n├── main.md            # Roadmap: goals, milestones, notes\n└── git-goals/&lt;branch&gt;.md  # Per-git-branch goal files\n```\n\n**Head tracking**: Per-worktree pointer at `.git/h5i/HEAD` (format: `ref: refs/h5i/context/&lt;name&gt;\\n`), mirroring Git's own HEAD mechanism.\n\n**Auto-follow**: When no `.git/h5i/PINNED` marker exists (default), every ctx command syncs HEAD to `refs/h5i/context/&lt;current-git-branch&gt;`, auto-creating the ref (forked from `main`) on first write.\n\n**Five research-backed capabilities** (ctx.rs:1-57):\n1. **DAG-based trace nodes** (CMV paper, arXiv:2602.22402): Nodes have `id`, `parent_ids`, `kind`, `content`, `timestamp`; merge points have 2 parents\n2. **Three-pass structurally-lossless pack** (CMV three-pass trimming)\n3. **Ephemeral trace entries** (Claude Code `/btw` pattern): cleared on context commit\n4. **Stable-prefix / dynamic-suffix serialization** (prompt-caching-aware)\n5. **Subagent-scoped sub-contexts** (named branches like `scope/&lt;name&gt;`)\n\n**Merging**: Uses libgit2's real three-way merge (produces 2-parent commit with conflict markers).\n\n**Test coverage**: 107 tests (1.9% of 5,724 lines)—solid, covering branch ops, metadata, DAG consistency, and merge logic.\n\n**Key types**: `TraceNode`, `TraceDag`, `GccContext`, `GccMetadata`, `ContextDiff`, `RelevantContext`, `SmartRecall`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. PARALLEL REF-BASED DATASTORES\n\n**Finding: 20+ distinct `refs/h5i/*` namespaces, each a separate git-backed sidecar store.**\n\n```\nrefs/h5i/context*          (N refs, auto-created per git-branch)\n  └─ context/main          (project-wide state, cross-branch goals)\n  └─ context/env           (environment workspace)\n  └─ context/feature       (feature branch workspace)\n  \nrefs/h5i/env               (singular, worktree metadata)\n  └─ /code                 (environment filesystem snapshots)\n  └─ /meta                 (environment manifest + policy state)\n\nrefs/h5i/ast               (singular, AST snapshots as Git blobs)\n\nrefs/h5i/memory            (singular, LLM-agent memory snapshots)\n\nrefs/h5i/msg               (singular, Agent Radio cross-agent messaging)\n                           (union-merge on divergent push/pull)\n\nrefs/h5i/objects           (singular, content-addressed evidence manifests)\n  └─ /_incoming/objects    (temporary staging during fetch)\n\nrefs/h5i/notes             (singular, per-commit inline notes)\n\nrefs/h5i/shadow            (per-timestamp WIP recovery branches)\n  └─ shadow/&lt;yyyymmdd-hhmmss&gt;\n\nrefs/h5i/_incoming         (temporary staging refs for sync)\n  └─ /_incoming/context\n  └─ /_incoming/objects\n```\n\n**Count**: 20 distinct ref families (some per-worktree, some shared, some ephemeral).\n\n**Purpose**: Each namespace is a read-write microstore optimized for its workload:\n- **ctx** = reasoning DAG (multi-branch, auto-follow)\n- **objects** = evidence manifests (append-only, policy-tagged)\n- **msg** = cross-agent operational handoffs (union-merged)\n- **ast** = structural snapshots (content-addressed, git-native)\n- **memory** = agent memory capsules (isolated by context branch)\n- **env** = sandbox worktree + policy state (linked to git worktree)\n\n**Sync mechanism**: `h5i share push` pushes all `refs/h5i/*` with a single refspec; `h5i share pull` fetches with auto-merge (notes/msg union-merge on divergence).\n\n---\n\n### 5. TESTING LANDSCAPE: 1,133 TESTS, UNEVEN COVERAGE\n\n**Total test count**:\n- **src/*.rs**: 871 tests (inline unit + integration)\n- **tests/*.rs**: 262 tests (end-to-end integration)\n- **Total**: 1,133 tests across ~69K lines of code (1.6% test:code ratio)\n\n**Well-tested subsystems** (&gt;1.5% coverage):\n| Module | Lines | Tests | % | Purpose |\n|--------|-------|-------|---|---------|\n| ctx.rs | 5724 | 107 | 1.9% | Context workspace DAG ops |\n| pr.rs | 3984 | 71 | 1.8% | GitHub PR tooling |\n| mcp.rs | 3302 | 63 | 1.9% | Model Context Protocol server |\n| objects.rs | 2610 | 55 | 2.1% | Evidence manifest store |\n| session_log.rs | 2326 | 46 | 1.9% | Session/churn tracking |\n| sandbox.rs | 2857 | 42 | 1.4% | Policy parsing, profile validation |\n| msg.rs | 2016 | 42 | 2.0% | Agent Radio messaging |\n\n**Severely undertested** (&lt;0.5% coverage):\n| Module | Lines | Tests | % | Risk |\n|--------|-------|-------|---|------|\n| server.rs | 5172 | 10 | 0.2% | **CRITICAL**: 47 web handlers; only high-level route tests |\n| main.rs | 10261 | 0 | 0.0% | **N/A**: CLI routing + dispatch; tested indirectly via integration |\n| env.rs | 4249 | 19 | 0.4% | **HIGH**: Sandbox lifecycle (create/run/apply) has end-to-end coverage via `env_integration.rs` (88 tests) |\n| supervisor.rs | 1010 | 9 | 0.8% | **MEDIUM**: seccomp-notify socket gate (narrow, specialized) |\n| container.rs | 1812 | 19 | 1.0% | **MEDIUM**: Podman/container backend (optional tier) |\n\n**Integration test suite** (`tests/*.rs`, 262 tests):\n- `env_integration.rs` (88 tests): **Full env lifecycle** (create, run, propose, apply, forensics)\n  - Tests sandbox policy enforcement, worktree isolation, provenance capture, and the full review/merge flow\n  - **NOT tested at unit level**: individual seccomp/Landlock rules, netns, cgroup enforcement\n  - Test runs sandbox API too (`sandbox_api.rs`, 4 tests)\n- `cli_integration.rs` (69 tests): CLI command routing, git interaction\n- `msg_integration.rs` (37 tests): Agent Radio union-merge, divergence handling\n- `objects_e2e.rs` (25 tests): Evidence manifest lifecycle\n\n**Sandbox security-critical subsystems**: 42 tests in `sandbox.rs` cover:\n- Profile parsing and precedence (`parses_the_design_doc_example_profile`)\n- Policy digest stability (`fsize_changes_the_policy_digest`)\n- Seccomp program compilation (`seccomp_deny_program_builds_and_blocks_io_uring`)\n- Isolation tier fallback logic (`effective_auto_never_picks_an_unrunnable_tier`)\n- Egress allowlist enforcement (`egress_allowlist_under_process_fails_closed`)\n- Secret grant normalization (`secret_grants_are_accepted_and_normalized`)\n\n**No functional security tests** (e.g., \"run confined code that tries to read /etc/shadow and verify it's blocked\") — all sandbox boundary validation is at the policy-AST / config level, not kernel-enforced-behavior level.\n\n---\n\n### 6. ARCHITECTURAL SUMMARY: \"ONE BINARY, MANY CONCERNS\"\n\n**Honest assessment:**\n\nh5i is NOT a git sidecar that crept into a monolith. It is a **deliberately integrated system** that fuses five orthogonal concerns into one reason-and-evidence loop:\n\n1. **Git operations** (repository.rs, objects.rs, session_log.rs) — evidence storage\n2. **Sandbox lifecycle** (env.rs, sandbox.rs, container.rs, supervisor.rs) — isolated execution\n3. **Reasoning memory** (ctx.rs, memory.rs, recall) — agent context tracking\n4. **Cross-agent messaging** (msg.rs) — multi-agent coordination via Git\n5. **Analytics / review** (server.rs, pr.rs, metadata.rs) — human-in-the-loop audit\n\n**Why one binary:**\n- All five concerns are tightly coupled: a single h5i commit captures all five in one atomic blob\n- Reasoning state (ctx) is **tied to execution isolation** (env) and **evidence** (objects)—you cannot split them without losing semantics\n- The CLI dispatch (`main.rs` with 59 subcommands) routes to handlers that are independently small; main.rs itself is glue, not business logic\n\n**The tension:**\n- **server.rs is under-tested** (0.2%) relative to its role; 47 handlers with only 10 tests invite refactor bugs\n- **env.rs / sandbox.rs are unit-light but integration-strong**: the real test is `env_integration.rs` (88 tests exercising the full create→run→propose→apply flow) plus sandbox-api (4 tests), not unit tests of policy parsing alone\n- **main.rs has zero tests** by design (it's CLI routing); all subcommand behavior is tested via CLI integration tests\n\n---\n\n### 7. KEY NUMBERS &amp; EVIDENCE\n\n| Metric | Value | Evidence |\n|--------|-------|----------|\n| Single binary | Yes | Cargo.toml: 1 `[[bin]]`, no feature gates, no conditional compilation of subcommands |\n| Top-level subcommands | 59 variants | main.rs:618–1510, `Commands` enum |\n| Distinct `refs/h5i/*` namespaces | 20 families | grep -rho across src/ (context*, env, ast, memory, msg, objects, notes, shadow, _incoming) |\n| Context refs | N per-branch | refs/h5i/context/{main,env,feature,...}; auto-created on first write |\n| Total LoC (src/) | 69,124 | wc -l src/*.rs |\n| Total tests | 1,133 | 871 inline + 262 integration |\n| Test:code ratio | 1.6% | 1,133 tests / 69,124 LoC |\n| server.rs handlers | 47 functions | grep \"^async fn\\|^fn\" |\n| server.rs test coverage | 0.2% | 10 tests / 5,172 lines |\n| ctx.rs test coverage | 1.9% | 107 tests / 5,724 lines (best-tested module) |\n| env.rs end-to-end tests | 88 tests | env_integration.rs (full lifecycle) |\n| Sandbox policy tests | 42 tests | sandbox.rs (no kernel-behavior validation) |\n| Feature flags | 0 | No `#[cfg(feature = ...)]` in code |\n| OS-level gates | 3 types | `#[cfg(target_os = \"linux\")]`, `#[cfg(unix)]`, `#[cfg(test)]` |\n\n---\n\n### 8. CONCLUSION\n\n**h5i is a monolithic, intentionally-unified system—not scope creep but design.** The single binary unifies Git-backed evidence storage, sandbox confinement, agent reasoning memory, cross-agent messaging, and human review into one atomic commit. Splitting it would fragment the semantics.\n\n**The testing skew** (server.rs at 0.2% vs. ctx.rs at 1.9%) reflects architectural priorities: business-logic modules (context, messaging, objects) are unit-tested heavily; infrastructure layers (web server, CLI dispatch, sandbox config parsing) are tested via end-to-end integration. This is defensible for web handlers (shallow coverage acceptable if integration tests exercise the routes) but risky for sandbox confinement (policy is tested, kernel enforcement is not).\n\n**Recommendation**: Increase server.rs test coverage to 2-3% (unit tests of handler logic, edge cases on JSON serialization, and error paths). Add functional sandbox security tests (confined-then-violated, not just \"policy parses correctly\").</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>46302</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>55</tool_uses><duration_ms>248481</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\n\nReview the design of this tool like Linus Torvalds\n\nok, let's tackle all of them","agent_id":"claude-code","usage":null},"test_metrics":null,"ast_hashes":null,"timestamp":"2026-06-18T17:04:11.985001868Z"}